Graphs: Basics
â€¢ A graph is a pair (V, E), where
  â€¢ V is a set of nodes, called vertices // ì •ì ë“¤ì˜ ì§‘í•© ì •ì ì€ ë…¸ë“œë¼ê³  ë¶ˆë¦¼ ê·¸ë˜í”„ ìœ„ì—ì„œ ìœ„ì¹˜ë¥¼ ë‚˜íƒ€ëƒ„
  â€¢ E is a collection of pairs of vertices, called edges // ê°„ì„ ë“¤ì˜ ì§‘í•©ì •ì ì‚¬ì´ë¥¼ ì—°ê²°í•¨, ë…¸ë“œê°„ì˜ ê´€ê³„ë¥¼ ë‚˜íƒ€ë‚¸ë‹¤.
â€¢ Vertices and edges are positions and store elements
â€¢ Example:
  â€¢ A vertex represents an airport and stores the three-letter airport code
  â€¢ An edge represents a flight route between two airports and stores the mileage of the route


Edge Types
  â€¢ Directed edge // ë°©í–¥ì´ ìˆë„¤ ì¶œë°œ ì§€ì  ì˜¤ë¦¬ì§„ê³¼ ëª©ì ì§€ê°€ ì¡´ì¬í•¨
  â€¢ ordered pair of vertices (u,v) 
  â€¢ first vertex u is the origin
  â€¢ second vertex v is the destination
  â€¢ e.g., a flight
â€¢ Undirected edge //ë°©í–¥ì´ ì—†ê³  ê·¸ëƒ¥ ê¸¸ì´ë¥¼ ë‚˜íƒ€ëƒ„
  â€¢ unordered pair of vertices (u,v) 
  â€¢ e.g., a flight route
â€¢ Directed graph
  â€¢ all the edges are directed
  â€¢ e.g., flight network
â€¢ Undirected graph
  â€¢ all the edges are undirected
  â€¢ e.g., route network
  

