â€¢ End vertices (or endpoints) of an edge 
  â€¢ U and V are the endpoints of a 
â€¢ Edges incident on a vertex 
  â€¢ a, d, and b are incident on V 
â€¢ Adjacent vertices 
  â€¢ U and V are adjacent 
â€¢ Degree of a vertex 
  â€¢ X has degree 5 
â€¢ Parallel edges 
  â€¢ h and i are parallel edges 
â€¢ Self-loop 
  â€¢ j is a self-loop


â€¢ Path
  â€¢ sequence of alternating vertices and edges
  â€¢ begins with a vertex
  â€¢ ends with a vertex
  â€¢ each edge is preceded and followed by its endpoints
â€¢ Simple path
  â€¢ path such that all its vertices and edges are distinct
â€¢ Examples
  â€¢ P1=(V,b,X,h,Z) is a simple path
  â€¢ P2=(U,c,W,e,X,g,Y,f,W,d,V) is a path that is not simple
  //ëŒì•„ê°€ëŠ” ë£¨íŠ¸ ì–ì•„ ê·¸ëŸ¬ë©´ not simple 

  
â€¢ Cycle //ì‚¬ì´í´ì€ ë§ëŠ”ë° ì¢€ ê¼¬ë¶ˆê¼¬ë¶ˆí•˜ê²Œ ëŒì•„ì„œ ê°ˆ ìˆ˜ë„ ìˆë‹¤.
  â€¢ circular sequence of alternating vertices and edges 
  â€¢ each edge is preceded and followed by its endpoints
â€¢ Simple cycle
  â€¢ cycle such that all its vertices and edges are distinct
â€¢ Examples
  â€¢ C1=(V,b,X,g,Y,f,W,c,U,a,ï‚¿) is a simple cycle
  â€¢ C2=(U,c,W,e,X,g,Y,f,W,d,V,a,ï‚¿) is a cycle that is not simple
â€¢ Note) Tree is a graph without cycles 


